# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: deutsches-institut-für-normung
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] An **acronym** is an abbreviation formed using the initial letters of a multi-word name or phrase.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Acronyms are often spelled with the initial letter of each word in all caps with no punctuation.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] In English, the word is used in two ways.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] In the narrow sense, an acronym is a sequence of letters (representing the initial letters of words in a phrase) when pronounced together as a single word, like *NASA*, *NATO*, or *laser*.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] In the broad sense, the term includes this kind of sequence when pronounced letter by letter (such as *GDP* or *USA*).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Sources that differentiate the two often call the former acronyms and the latter **initialisms** or **alphabetisms**.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] However, *acronym* is popularly used to refer to either concept, and both senses of the term are attributed as far back as the 1940s.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Dictionary and style-guide editors dispute whether the term *acronym* can be legitimately applied to abbreviations which are not pronounced as words, and there is no general agreement on standard acronym spacing, casing, and punctuation.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] The phrase that the acronym stands for is called its *expansion*.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] The *meaning* of an acronym includes both its expansion and the meaning of its expansion.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] The word *acronym* is formed from the Greek roots *akro-*, meaning 'height, summit, or tip', and *-nym*, 'name'.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] This neoclassical compound appears to have originated in German, with attestations for the German form *Akronym* appearing as early as 1921.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Citations in English date to a 1940 translation of a novel by the German writer Lion Feuchtwanger.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] English lexicography and style guides differ on whether *acronym* should apply only to abbreviations pronounced as ordinary words or also to letter-by-letter initialisms.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Some authorities accept or record the broader sense; others restrict *acronym* to word-pronounced forms and prefer *initialism* (or simply *abbreviation*) for the rest.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Among sources that acknowledge the broader sense, attitudes range from neutral recording to prescriptive criticism.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Some mainstream English dictionaries from across the English-speaking world affirm a sense of *acronym* that does not require its pronunciation as a word.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] English language usage and style guides which have entries for *acronym* generally criticize the usage that refers to forms that are not pronounceable words.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] In contrast, some style guides do support it, whether explicitly or implicitly.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] The 1994 edition of *Merriam-Webster's Dictionary of English Usage* defends the usage on the basis of a claim that dictionaries do not make a distinction.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] The BuzzFeed style guide describes CBS and PBS as "acronyms ending in S".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Most of the dictionary entries and style guide recommendations regarding the term *acronym* in the twentieth century did not explicitly acknowledge or support the expansive sense.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] The Merriam–Webster's Dictionary of English Usage from 1994 is one of the earliest publications to advocate for the expansive sense, and all the major dictionary editions that include a sense of *acronym* equating it with *initialism* were first published in the twenty-first century.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] The 1989 edition of the *Oxford English Dictionary* only included the exclusive sense for *acronym* and its earliest citation was from 1943.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] In early December 2010, Duke University researcher Stephen Goranson published a citation for *acronym* to the American Dialect Society e-mail discussion list which refers to *PGN* being pronounced "pee-gee-enn", antedating English language usage of the word to 1940.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Linguist Ben Zimmer then mentioned this citation in his December 16, 2010 "On Language" column about acronyms in *The New York Times Magazine*.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] By 2011, the publication of the 3rd edition of the *Oxford English Dictionary* added the expansive sense to its entry for *acronym* and included the 1940 citation.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] As the *Oxford English Dictionary* structures the senses in order of chronological development, it now gives the "initialism" sense first.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Acronymy, like retronymy, is a linguistic process that has existed throughout history but for which there was little to no naming, conscious attention, or systematic analysis until relatively recent times.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Like retronymy, it became much more common in the twentieth century than it had formerly been.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] American Telephone and Telegraph Company → AT&T).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Some well-known commercial examples dating from the 1890s through 1920s include "Nabisco" ("National Biscuit Company"), "Esso" (from "S.O.", from "Standard Oil"), and "Sunoco" ("Sun Oil Company").
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Another field for the adoption of acronyms was modern warfare, with its many highly technical terms.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] The widespread, frequent use of acronyms across the whole range of linguistic registers is relatively new in most languages, becoming increasingly evident since the mid-twentieth century.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] As literacy spread and technology produced a constant stream of new and complex terms, abbreviations became increasingly convenient.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] The *Oxford English Dictionary* (*OED*) records the first printed use of the word *initialism* as occurring in 1899, but it did not come into general use until 1965, well after *acronym* had become common.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] In English, acronyms *pronounced as words* may be a twentieth-century phenomenon.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Linguist David Wilton in *Word Myths: Debunking Linguistic Urban Legends* claims that "forming words from acronyms is a distinctly twentieth- (and now twenty-first-) century phenomenon.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] There is only one known pre-twentieth-century [English] word with an acronymic origin and it was in vogue for only a short time in 1886.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] The use of Latin and Neo-Latin terms in vernaculars has been pan-European and pre-dates modern English.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] The earliest example of a word derived from an acronym listed by the *OED* is "abjud" (now "abjad"), formed from the original first four letters of the Arabic alphabet in the late eighteenth century.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Some acrostics pre-date this, however, such as the Restoration witticism arranging the names of some members of Charles II's Committee for Foreign Affairs to produce the "CABAL" ministry.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Acronyms are used most often to abbreviate names of organizations and long or frequently referenced terms.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] The armed forces and government agencies frequently employ acronyms; some well-known examples from the United States are among the "alphabet agencies" (jokingly referred to as "alphabet soup") created under the New Deal by Franklin D.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Business and industry also coin acronyms prolifically.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] The rapid advance of science and technology also drives the usage, as new inventions and concepts with multiword names create a demand for shorter, more pronounceable names.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] One representative example, from the U.S.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Navy, is "COMCRUDESPAC", which stands for "commander, cruisers destroyers Pacific"; it is also seen as "ComCruDesPac".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Acronym use has been further popularized by text messaging on mobile phones with short message service (SMS), and instant messenger (IM).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] To fit messages into the 160-character SMS limit, and to save time, acronyms such as "GF" ("girlfriend"), "LOL" ("laughing out loud"), and "DL" ("download" or "down low") have become popular.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Some prescriptivists disdain texting acronyms and abbreviations as decreasing clarity, or as failure to use "pure" or "proper" English.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Others point out that languages have always continually changed, and argue that acronyms should be embraced as inevitable, or as innovation that adapts the language to changing circumstances.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] In this view, the modern practice is just the "proper" English of the current generation of speakers, much like the earlier abbreviation of corporation names on ticker tape or newspapers.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Exact pronunciation of "word acronyms" (those pronounced as words rather than sounded out as individual letters) often vary by speaker population.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] These may be regional, occupational, or generational differences, or simply personal preference.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] For instance, there have been decades of online debate about how to pronounce GIF (/ɡɪf/ or /dʒɪf/) and BIOS (/ˈbaɪoʊs/, /ˈbaɪoʊz/, or /ˈbaɪɒs/).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Pronunciation may even vary within a single speaker's vocabulary, depending on narrow contexts.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] As an example, the database programming language SQL is usually said as three letters, but in reference to Microsoft's implementation is traditionally pronounced like the word *sequel*.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] In writing for a broad audience, the words of an acronym are typically written out in full at its first occurrence within a given text.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Expansion at first use (EAFU) benefits readers unfamiliar with the acronym.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Another text aid is an abbreviation key which lists and expands all acronyms used, a reference for readers who skipped past the first use.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] (This is especially important for paper media, where no search utility is available to find the first use.) It also gives students a convenient review list to memorize the important acronyms introduced in a textbook chapter.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Expansion at first use and abbreviation keys originated in the print era, but they are equally useful for electronic text.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] While acronyms provide convenience and succinctness for specialists, they often degenerate into confusing jargon.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] This may be intentional, to exclude readers without domain-specific knowledge.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] New acronyms may also confuse when they coincide with an already existing acronym having a different meaning.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Medical literature has been struggling to control the proliferation of acronyms, including efforts by the American Academy of Dermatology.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Acronyms are often taught as mnemonic devices: for example the colors of the rainbow are ROY G.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] BIV (red, orange, yellow, green, blue, indigo, violet).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] They are also used as mental checklists: in aviation GUMPS stands for gas-undercarriage-mixture-propeller-seat belts.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Other mnemonic acronyms include HOMES (for the North American Great Lakes) in geography, PAVPANIC in English grammar, and PEMDAS/BODMAS in mathematics.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] It is not uncommon for acronyms to be cited in a kind of false etymology, called a folk etymology, for a word.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Such etymologies persist in popular culture but have no factual basis in historical linguistics, and are examples of language-related urban legends.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] For example, "cop" is commonly cited as being derived, it is presumed, from "constable on patrol", and "posh" from "port outward, starboard home".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] With some of these specious expansions, the "belief" that the etymology is acronymic has clearly been tongue-in-cheek among many citers, as with "gentlemen only, ladies forbidden" for "golf", although many other (more credulous) people have uncritically taken it for fact.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Taboo words in particular commonly have such false etymologies: "shit" from "ship/store high in transit" or "special high-intensity training" and "fuck" from "for unlawful carnal knowledge", or "fornication under consent/command of the king".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] In English, abbreviations have previously been marked by a wide variety of punctuation.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Obsolete forms include using an overbar or colon to show the ellipsis of letters following the initial part.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] The forward slash is still common in many dialects for some fixed expressions—such as in *w/* for "with" or *A/C* for "air conditioning"—while only infrequently being used to abbreviate new terms.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] The apostrophe is common for grammatical contractions (e.g.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] *don't*, *y'all*, and *ain't*) and for contractions marking unusual pronunciations (e.g.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] *a'ight*, *cap'n*, and *fo'c'sle* for "all right", "captain", and "forecastle").
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] By the early twentieth century, it was standard to use a full stop/period/point, especially in the cases of initialisms and acronyms.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Previously, especially for Latin abbreviations, this was done with a full space between every full word (e.g.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] This even included punctuation after both Roman and Arabic numerals to indicate their use in place of the full names of each number (e.g.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Both conventions have fallen out of common use in all dialects of English, except in places where an Arabic decimal includes a medial decimal point.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Particularly in British and Commonwealth English, all such punctuation marking acronyms and other capitalized abbreviations is now uncommon and considered either unnecessary or incorrect.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] The presence of all-capital letters is now thought sufficient to indicate the nature of the *UK*, the *EU*, and the *UN*.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Forms such as *the U.S.A.* for "the United States of America" are now considered to indicate American or North American English.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Even within those dialects, such punctuation is becoming increasingly uncommon.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Some style guides, such as that of the BBC, no longer require punctuation to show ellipsis; some even proscribe it.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Nevertheless, some influential style guides, many of them American, still require periods in certain instances.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] For example, *The New York Times Manual of Style and Usage* recommends following each segment with a period when the letters are pronounced individually, as in "K.G.B.", but not when pronounced as a word, as in "NATO".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] The logic of this style is that the pronunciation is reflected graphically by the punctuation scheme.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] When a multiple-letter abbreviation is formed from a single word, periods are in general not used, although they may be common in informal usage.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] "TV", for example, may stand for a *single* word ("television", for instance), and is in general spelled without punctuation (except in the plural).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Although "PS" stands for the single English word "postscript" or the Latin *postscriptum*, it is often spelled with periods ("P.S.") as if parsed as Latin *post scriptum* instead.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] The slash ('/', or *solidus*) is sometimes used to separate the letters in an acronym, as in "N/A" ("not applicable, not available") and "c/o" ("care of").
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Inconveniently long words used frequently in related contexts can be represented according to their letter count as a numeronym.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] For example, "i18n" abbreviates "internationalization", a computer-science term for adapting software for worldwide use; the "18" represents the 18 letters that come between the first and the last in "internationalization".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Similarly, "localization" can be abbreviated "l10n"; "multilingualization" "m17n"; and "accessibility" "a11y".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] In addition to the use of a specific number replacing that many letters, the more general "x" can be used to replace an unspecified number of letters.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Examples include "Crxn" for "crystallization" and the series familiar to physicians for history, diagnosis, and treatment ("hx", "dx", "tx").
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Terms relating to a command structure may also sometimes use this formatting, for example gold, silver, and bronze levels of command in UK policing being referred to as Gx, Sx, and Bx.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] There is a question about how to pluralize acronyms.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Often a writer will add an 's' following an apostrophe, as in "PC's".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Turabian's *A Manual for Writers of Research Papers, Theses, and Dissertations*, writing about style in academic writings, allows for an apostrophe to form plural acronyms "only when an abbreviation contains internal periods or both capital and lowercase letters".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Turabian would therefore prefer "DVDs" and "URLs" but not "Ph.D.s".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Possessive plurals that also include apostrophes for mere pluralization and periods appear especially complex: for example, "the C.D.'s' labels" (the labels of the compact discs).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] In some instances, however, an apostrophe may increase clarity: for example, if the final letter of an abbreviation is "S", as in "SOS's" (although abbreviations ending with S can also take "-es", e.g.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] "SOSes"), or when pluralizing an abbreviation that has periods.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] A particularly rich source of options arises when the plural of an acronym would normally be indicated in a word other than the final word if spelled out in full.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] A classic example is "Member of Parliament", which in plural is "Members of Parliament".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] It is possible then to abbreviate this as "M's P", which was fairly common in mid-twentieth-century Australian news writing (or similar), and used by former Australian Prime Minister Ben Chifley.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] This usage is less common than forms with "s" at the end, such as "MPs", and may appear dated or pedantic.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] In common usage, therefore, "weapons of mass destruction" becomes "WMDs", "prisoners of war" becomes "POWs", and "runs batted in" becomes "RBIs".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Abbreviations that come from single, rather than multiple, words—such as "TV" ("television")—are usually pluralized without apostrophes ("two TVs"); most writers feel that the apostrophe should be reserved for the possessive ("the TV's antenna").
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] In some languages, the convention of doubling the letters in the acronym is used to indicate plural words: for example, the Spanish *EE.UU.*, for *Estados Unidos* ('United States').
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] This old convention is still sometimes followed for a limited number of English abbreviations, such as *SS.* for *Saints*, *pp.* for the plural of 'pages', or *mss.* for *manuscripts*.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] The most common capitalization scheme seen with acronyms is all-uppercase (all caps).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Small caps are sometimes used to make the run of capital letters seem less jarring to the reader.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] For example, the style of some American publications, including the *Atlantic Monthly* and *USA Today*, is to use small caps for acronyms longer than three letters; thus "U.S." and "FDR" are set in normal caps, but "nato" is set in small caps.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] The acronyms "AD" and "BC" are often smallcapped as well, as in: "From 4004 bc to ad 525".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Where an acronym has linguistically taken on an identity as regular word, the acronym may use normal case rules, e.g. it would appear generally in lower case, but with an initial capital when starting a sentence or when in a title.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Once knowledge of the words underlying such an acronym has faded from common recall, the acronym may be termed an **anacronym**.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Examples of anacronyms are the words "scuba", "radar", and "laser".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] The word "an*acro*nym" should not be confused with the word "an*achro*nym", which is a type of misnomer.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Words derived from an acronym by affixing are typically expressed in mixed case, so the root acronym is clear.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] For example, "pre-WWII politics", "post-NATO world", "DNase".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] In some cases a derived acronym may also be expressed in mixed case.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] For example, "messenger RNA" and "transfer RNA" become "mRNA" and "tRNA".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Some publications choose to capitalize only the first letter of acronyms, reserving all-caps styling for initialisms, writing the pronounced acronyms "Nato" and "Aids" in mixed case, but the initialisms "USA" and "FBI" in all caps.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] For example, this is the style used in *The Guardian*, and *BBC News* typically edits to this style (though its official style guide, dating from 2003, still recommends all-caps).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] The logic of this style is that the pronunciation is reflected graphically by the capitalization scheme.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] However, it conflicts with conventional English usage of first-letter upper-casing as a marker of proper names in many cases.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] For example, *AIDS* stands for *acquired immunodeficiency syndrome*, which is not a proper name, while *Aids* is in the style of one.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Some style manuals also base the letters' case on their number.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] While abbreviations typically exclude the initials of short function words (such as "and", "or", "of", or "to"), this is not always the case.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Sometimes function words are included to make a pronounceable acronym, such as CORE (Congress of Racial Equality).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Sometimes the letters representing these words are written in lower case, such as in the cases of "TfL" ("Transport for London") and *LotR* (*The Lord of the Rings*); this usually occurs when the acronym represents a multi-word proper noun.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Numbers (both cardinal and ordinal) in names are often represented by digits rather than initial letters, as in "4GL" ("fourth generation language") or "G77" ("Group of 77").
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Large numbers may use metric prefixes, as with "Y2K" for "Year 2000".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Exceptions using initials for numbers include "TLA" ("three-letter acronym/abbreviation") and "GoF" ("Gang of Four").
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Authors of expository writing will sometimes capitalize or otherwise distinctively format the initials of the expansion for pedagogical emphasis (for example, writing: "the onset of Congestive Heart Failure (CHF)" or "the onset of **c**ongestive **h**eart **f**ailure (CHF)").
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p01] Capitalization like this, however, conflicts with the convention of English orthography, which generally reserves capitals in the middle of sentences for proper nouns; when following the AMA Manual of Style, this would instead be rendered as "the onset of congestive heart failure (CHF)".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Some apparent acronyms or other abbreviations do not stand for anything and cannot be expanded to some meaning.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Such pseudo-acronyms may be pronunciation-based, such as "BBQ" (*bee-bee-cue*), for "barbecue", and "K9" (*kay-nine*) for "canine".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Pseudo-acronyms also frequently develop as "orphan initialisms": an existing acronym is redefined as a non-acronymous name, severing its link to its previous meaning.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] For example, the letters of the "SAT", a US college entrance test originally dubbed "Scholastic Aptitude Test", no longer officially stand for anything.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] This is common with companies that want to retain brand recognition while moving away from an outdated image: American Telephone and Telegraph became AT&T and British Petroleum became BP.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] *Russia Today* has rebranded itself as *RT*.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] American Movie Classics has simply rebranded itself as AMC.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Genzyme Transgenics Corporation became GTC Biotherapeutics, Inc.; The Learning Channel became TLC; MTV dropped the name Music Television out of its brand; and American District Telegraph became simply known as ADT.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] "Kentucky Fried Chicken" went partway, re-branding itself with its initialism "KFC" to de-emphasize the role of frying in the preparation of its signature dishes, though they have since returned to using both interchangeably.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] The East Coast Hockey League became the ECHL when it expanded to include cities in the western United States prior to the 2003–2004 season.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Pseudo-acronyms may have advantages in international markets: for example, some national affiliates of International Business Machines are legally incorporated with "IBM" in their names (for example, IBM Canada) to avoid translating the full name into local languages.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Likewise, UBS is the name of the merged Union Bank of Switzerland and Swiss Bank Corporation, and HSBC has replaced the long name Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corporation.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] The India-based JSW Group of companies is another example of the original name (Jindal South West Group) being re-branded into a pseudo-acronym while expanding into other geographical areas in and outside of India.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Rebranding can lead to redundant acronym syndrome, as when Trustee Savings Bank became TSB Bank, or when Railway Express Agency became REA Express.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] A few high-tech companies have taken the redundant acronym to the extreme: for example, ISM Information Systems Management Corp. and SHL Systemhouse Ltd.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Examples in entertainment include the television shows *CSI: Crime Scene Investigation* and *Navy: NCIS* ("Navy" was dropped in the second season), where the redundancy was likely designed to educate new viewers as to what the initials stood for.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] In some cases, while the initials in an acronym may stay the same, for what those letters stand may change.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] A *backronym* (or *bacronym*) is a phrase that is constructed "after the fact" from a previously existing word.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] For example, the novelist and critic Anthony Burgess once proposed that the word "book" ought to stand for "box of organized knowledge".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] A classic real-world example of this is the name of the predecessor to the Apple Macintosh, the Apple Lisa, which was said to refer to "Local Integrated Software Architecture", but was actually named after Steve Jobs' daughter, born in 1978.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Contrived acronyms are deliberately designed to be apt for the thing being named (by having a dual meaning or by borrowing the positive connotations of an existing word).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Some examples of contrived acronyms are *USA PATRIOT*, *CAN SPAM*, *CAPTCHA*, *DOGE* and *ACT UP*.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] The clothing company French Connection began referring to itself as *fcuk*, standing for "French Connection United Kingdom".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] The company then created T-shirts and several advertising campaigns that exploit the acronym's similarity to the taboo word "fuck".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Contrived acronyms find frequent use as names of fictional agencies, with a famous example being frequent James Bond antagonist organization SPECTRE (Special Executive for Counterintelligence, Terrorism, Revenge and Extortion).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Department of Defense's Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) is known for developing contrived acronyms to name projects, including *RESURRECT*, *NIRVANA*, and *DUDE*.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] The short-form names of clinical trials and other scientific studies constitute a large class of acronyms that includes many contrived examples, as well as many with a partial rather than complete correspondence of letters to expansion components.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Examples widely known in medicine include the ALLHAT trial (Antihypertensive and Lipid-Lowering Treatment to Prevent Heart Attack Trial) and the CHARM trial (Candesartan in Heart Failure: Assessment of Reduction in Mortality and Morbidity).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] However, the purpose of clinical trial acronyms, as with gene and protein symbols, is simply to have a syntactically usable and easily recalled short name to complement the long name that is often syntactically unusable and not memorized.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] It is useful for the short name to give a reminder of the long name, which supports the reasonable censure of "cutesy" examples that provide little to no hint of it.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] But beyond that reasonably close correspondence, the short name's chief utility is in functioning cognitively as a name, rather than being a cryptic and forgettable string, albeit faithful to the matching of letters.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] At least one study has evaluated the citation impact and other traits of acronym-named trials compared with others, finding both good aspects (mnemonic help, name recall) and potential flaws (connotatively driven bias).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Some acronyms are chosen deliberately to avoid a name considered undesirable: For example, *Verliebt in Berlin* (*ViB*), a German telenovela, was first intended to be *Alles nur aus Liebe* ('All for Love'), but was changed to avoid the resultant acronym *ANAL*.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Likewise, the Computer Literacy and Internet Technology qualification is known as *CLaIT*, rather than *CLIT*.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] In Canada, the Canadian Conservative Reform Alliance (Party) was quickly renamed to the "Canadian Reform Conservative Alliance" when its opponents pointed out that its initials spelled CCRAP (pronounced "see crap").
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Two Irish institutes of technology (Galway and Tralee) chose different acronyms from other institutes when they were upgraded from regional technical colleges.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Tralee RTC became the Institute of Technology Tralee (ITT), as opposed to Tralee Institute of Technology (TIT).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Galway RTC became Galway-Mayo Institute of Technology (GMIT), as opposed to Galway Institute of Technology (GIT).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] The charity sports organization Team in Training is known as "TNT" and not "TIT".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Technological Institute of Textile & Sciences, however, is still known as "TITS".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] George Mason University was planning to name their law school the "Antonin Scalia School of Law" (ASSOL) in honor of the late Antonin Scalia, only to change it to the "Antonin Scalia Law School" later.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] A **macronym**, or **nested acronym**, is an acronym in which one or more letters stand for acronyms (or abbreviations) themselves.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] The word "macronym" is a portmanteau of "macro-" and "acronym".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Some macronyms can be multiply nested: the second-order acronym points to another one further down a hierarchy.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] VITAL, for example, which expands to "VHDL Initiative Towards ASIC Libraries" is a total of 15 words when fully expanded.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Fully expanded, "RARS" might thus become "Regional Advanced Television Infrared Observational Satellite Operational Vertical Sounder Retransmission Service", which would produce the much more unwieldy acronym "RATIOSOVSRS".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] The latter are fully reducible in an attempt to "spell everything out and avoid all abbreviations", but the former are irreducible in that respect; they can be annotated with parenthetical explanations, but they cannot be eliminated from speech or writing in any useful or practical way.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] The name is thus itself more symbol than acronym, and its expansion cannot replace it while preserving its function in natural syntax as a name within a clause clearly parsable by human readers or listeners.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] A special type of macronym, the recursive acronym, has letters whose expansion refers back to the macronym itself.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] One of the earliest examples appears in *The Hacker's Dictionary* as MUNG, which stands for "MUNG Until No Good".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] With English terminology, discussions of languages with syllabic or logographic writing systems (such as Chinese, Japanese, and Korean), "acronyms" describe the short forms that take selected characters from a multi-character word.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] For example, in Chinese, 'university' (大學/大学, lit.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] 'great learning') is usually abbreviated simply as 大 ('great') when used with the name of the institute.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] So 'Peking University' (北京大学) is commonly shortened to 北大 (lit.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] 'north-great') by also only taking the first character of *Peking*, the "northern capital" (北京; *Beijing*).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] In some cases, however, other characters than the first can be selected.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] For example, the local short form of 'Hong Kong University' (香港大學) uses *Kong* (港大) rather than *Hong*.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Many aspects of academics in Korea follow similar acronym patterns as Chinese, owing to the two languages' commonalities, like using the word for 'big' or 'great' i.e.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] *dae* (대), to refer to universities (대학; *daehak*, literally 'great learning' although 'big school' is an acceptable alternate).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] They can be interpreted similarly to American university appellations, such as "UPenn" or "Texas Tech".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Some acronyms are shortened forms of the school's name, like how Hongik University (홍익대학교, *Hongik Daehakgyo*) is shortened to *Hongdae* (홍대, 'Hong, the big [school]' or 'Hong-U') Other acronyms can refer to the university's main subject, e.g.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Korea National University of Education (한국교원대학교, *Hanguk Gyowon Daehakgyo*) is shortened to *Gyowondae* (교원대, 'Big Ed.' or 'Ed.-U').
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Other schools use a Koreanized version of their English acronym.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] The Korea Advanced Institute of Science and Technology (한국과학기술원, *Hanguk Gwahak Gisulwon*) is referred to as KAIST (카이스트, *Kaiseuteu*) in both English and Korean.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] The 3 most prestigious schools in Korea are known as SKY (스카이, *seukai*), combining the first letter of their English names (**S**eoul National, **K**orea, and **Y**onsei Universities).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] In addition, the College Scholastic Ability Test (대학수학능력시험, *Daehak Suhang Neungryeok Siheom*) is shortened to *Suneung* (수능, 'S.A.').
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] The Japanese language makes extensive use of abbreviations, but only some of these are acronyms.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Chinese-based words (Sino-Japanese vocabulary) use similar acronym formation to Chinese, like *Tōdai* (東大) for *Tōkyō Daigaku* (東京大学, *Tokyo University*).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] It is not always the case that the first character of each word is used, as in Saikyō for 埼京, from *Saitama* + *Tōkyō* (埼玉＋東京), which uses the second character of 東京.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Non-Chinese foreign borrowings (gairaigo) are instead frequently abbreviated as clipped compounds, rather than acronyms, using several initial sounds.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] This is visible in katakana transcriptions of foreign words, but is also found with native words (written in hiragana).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] For example, the *Pokémon* media franchise's name originally stood for "pocket monsters" (**ポケ**ット·**モン**スター [po-ke-tto-mon-su-tā] (arrow for r) ポケモン), which is still the long-form of the name in Japanese, or "wāpuro" for "word processor" (**ワー**ド·**プロ**セッサー [wā-do-pu-ro-se-ssā] (arrow for r) ワープロ).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] To a greater degree than English, German often uses syllabic abbreviations instead of acronyms.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Some examples are *Gestapo* rather than *GSP* (for *Geheime Staatspolizei*, 'Secret State Police'); *Flak* rather than *FAK* (for *Fliegerabwehrkanone*, 'anti-aircraft gun'); and *Kripo* rather than *KP* (for *Kriminalpolizei*, 'detective division police').
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] The overuse of such contractions has been mockingly labeled *Aküfi* (for *Abkürzungsfimmel*, 'strange habit of abbreviating').
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Examples of *Aküfi* include *Vokuhila* (for *vorne kurz, hinten lang*, 'short in the front, long in the back', i.e., a mullet haircut) and the mocking of Adolf Hitler's title as *Gröfaz* (*Größter Feldherr aller Zeiten*, 'Greatest General of all Time').
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Examples (keeping in mind that Hebrew reads right-to-left): ארה״ב (for ארצות הברית, the United States); ברה״מ (for ברית המועצות, the Soviet Union); ראשל״צ (for ראשון לציון, Rishon LeZion); ביה״ס (for בית הספר, the school).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] An example that takes only the initial letters from its component words is צה״ל (*Tzahal*, for צבא הגנה לישראל, Israel Defense Forces).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] In inflected forms, the abbreviation sign *gershayim* remains between the second-last and last letters of the non-inflected form of the acronym (e.g.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] 'report', singular: דו״ח, plural: דו״חות; 'squad commander', masculine: מ״כ, feminine: מ״כית).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] There is also a widespread use of acronyms in Indonesia in every aspect of social life.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Some acronyms are considered formal (or officially adopted), while many more are considered informal, slang, or colloquial.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] The capital's metropolitan area (Jakarta and its surrounding satellite regions), *Jabodetabek*, is another acronym.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] This stands for *Jakarta-Bogor-Depok-Tangerang-Bekasi*.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Many highways are also named by the acronym method, e.g.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] *Jalan Tol* ('Toll Road'), *Jagorawi* (*Jakarta-Bogor-Ciawi*), *Purbaleunyi* (*Purwakarta-Bandung-Cileunyi*), and *Joglo Semar* (*Jogja-Solo-Semarang*).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] In some languages, especially those that use certain alphabets, many acronyms come from the governmental use, particularly in the military and law enforcement services.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] The Indonesian military (TNI – *Tentara Nasional Indonesia*) and Indonesian police (POLRI – *Kepolisian Republik Indonesia*) are known for heavy acronyms use.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Although not as common as in its sister language Indonesian, a number of Malaysian (*Bahasa Malaysia*) words are formed by merging two words, such as *tadika* from *taman didikan kanak-kanak* ('kindergarten') and *pawagam* from *panggung wayang gambar*.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] This, however, has been less prevalent in the modern era, in contrary to Indonesian.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] It is still often for names such as organisation names, among the most famous being MARA from *Majlis Amanah Rakyat* ('People's Trust Council'), a government agency in Malaysia.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Rules in writing initialisms in Malaysian differ based on its script.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] In its Latin form, the initialism would be spelt much like in English, using capitals written without any spacing, such as TNB for *Tenaga Nasional Berhad*.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] In Jawi, however, initialisms differ depending on the source language.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] For Malay initialisms, the initial Jawi letters would be written separated by a period such as د.ب.ڤ for ديوان بهاس دان ڤوستاک.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] If the initialism is from a different language, however, it would be written by transliterating each letter from the original language, such as عيم.سي.عيم.سي. for MCMC, or الفا.ڤي.ثيتا for Α.Π.Θ.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Acronyms that use parts of words (not necessarily syllables) are commonplace in Russian as well, e.g. Газпром (*Gazprom*), for Газовая промышленность (*Gazovaya promyshlennost*, 'gas industry').
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Most commonly they are pronounced as words, unless they lack vowels, in which case they are pronounced by letters e.g. ФСБ (*ef-es-beh*, 'FSB'), США (*seh-sheh-ah*, USA).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Some foreigh acronyms became own words, such as айти (*IT*) and пиар (*PR*).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Historically, *OTMA* was an acronym sometimes used by the daughters of Emperor Nicholas II of Russia and his consort, Alexandra Feodorovna, as a group nickname for themselves, built from the first letter of each girl's name in the order of their births: Olga, Tatiana, Maria, and Anastasia.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] In Swahili, acronyms are common for naming organizations such as *TUKI*, which stands for *Taasisi ya Uchunguzi wa Kiswahili* ('Institute for Swahili Research').
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Multiple initial letters (often the initial syllable of words) are often drawn together, as seen more in some languages than others.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] In Vietnamese, which has an abundance of compound words, initialisms are very commonly used for both proper and common nouns.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Longer examples include *CHXHCNVN* (*Cộng hòa Xã hội chủ nghĩa Việt Nam*, 'Socialist Republic of Vietnam') and *MTDTGPMNVN* (*Mặt trận Dân tộc Giải phóng miền Nam Việt Nam*, 'Liberation Army of South Vietnam or the National Liberation Front of South Vietnam').
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Long initialisms have become widespread in legal contexts in Vietnam, for example *TTLT-VKSNDTC-TANDTC*.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] It is also common for a writer to coin an ad hoc initialism for repeated use in an article.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Each letter in an initialism corresponds to one morpheme, that is, one syllable.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] When the first letter of a syllable has a tone mark or other diacritic, the diacritic may be omitted from the initialism, for example *ĐNA* or *ĐNÁ* for *Đông Nam Á* ('Southeast Asia') and *LMCA* or *LMCÂ* for *Liên minh châu Âu* ('European Union').
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] The letter *Ư* is often replaced by *W* in initialisms to avoid confusion with *U*, for example *UBTWMTTQVN* or *UBTƯMTTQVN* for *Ủy ban Trung ương Mặt trận Tổ quốc Việt Nam* ('Central Committee of the Vietnamese Fatherland Front').
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Initialisms are purely a written convenience, being pronounced the same way as their expansions.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] As the names of many Vietnamese letters are disyllabic, it would be less convenient to pronounce an initialism by its individual letters.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Acronyms pronounced as words are rare in Vietnamese, occurring when an acronym itself is borrowed from another language.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Examples include *SIĐA* (pronounced [s̪i˧ ˀɗaː˧]), a respelling of the French acronym *SIDA* ('AIDS'); *VOA* (pronounced [vwaː˧]), a literal reading of the English initialism for 'Voice of America'; and *NASA* (pronounced [naː˧ zaː˧]), borrowed directly from the English acronym.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] As in Chinese, many compound words can be shortened to the first syllable when forming a longer word.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] For example, the term *Việt Cộng* is derived from the first syllables of *Việt Nam* ('Vietnam') and *Cộng sản* ('communist').
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] This mechanism is limited to Sino-Vietnamese vocabulary.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Unlike with Chinese, such clipped compounds are considered to be portmanteau words or blend words rather than acronyms or initialisms, because the Vietnamese alphabet still requires each component word to be written as more than one character.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] In languages where nouns are declined, various methods are used.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] The process above is similar to the way that hyphens are used for clarity in English when prefixes are added to acronyms: thus *pre-NATO policy* (rather than *preNATO*).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] In languages such as Scottish Gaelic and Irish, where lenition (initial consonant mutation) is commonplace, acronyms must also be modified in situations where case and context dictate it.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] In the case of Scottish Gaelic, a lower-case *h* is often added after the initial consonant; for example, 'BBC Scotland' in the genitive case would be written as *BhBC Alba*, with the acronym pronounced *VBC*.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/acronym-p02] Likewise, the Gaelic acronym for *telebhisean* 'television' is *TBh*, pronounced *TV*, as in English.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] The **American National Standards Institute** (**ANSI**) is a private nonprofit organization that oversees the development of voluntary consensus standards for products, services, processes, systems, and personnel in the United States.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] The organization also coordinates U.S. standards with international standards so that American products can be used worldwide.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI accredits standards that are developed by representatives of other standards organizations, government agencies, consumer groups, companies, and others.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] These standards ensure that the characteristics and performance of products are consistent, that people use the same definitions and terms, and that products are tested the same way.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI also accredits standards developing organizations (SDOs) and provides a searchable directory of accredited standards developers (ASDs).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI similarly accredits organizations that carry out product or personnel certification in accordance with requirements defined in international standards.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] The organization's headquarters are in Washington, D.C.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's operations office is located in New York City.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] The ANSI annual operating budget is funded by the sale of publications, membership dues and fees, accreditation services, fee-based programs, and international standards programs.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] Many ANSI regulations are incorporated by reference into United States federal statutes (i.e. by OSHA regulations referring to individual ANSI specifications).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI does not make these standards publicly available, and charges money for access to these documents; it further claims that it is copyright infringement for them to be provided to the public by others free of charge.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] These assertions have been the subject of criticism and litigation.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI was most likely formed in 1918, when five engineering societies and three government agencies founded the **American Engineering Standards Committee** (**AESC**).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] In 1928, the AESC became the **American Standards Association** (**ASA**).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] In 1966, the ASA was reorganized and became the **United States of America Standards Institute** (**USASI**).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] In February 1969, Ralph Nader harshly criticized the USASI in public remarks as "manifestly deceptive" in several different ways.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] He specifically attacked the name USASI as improperly implying some kind of official connection with the federal government of the United States.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] had been members of the United Engineering Society (UES).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] At the behest of the AIEE, they invited the U.S. government Departments of War, Navy (combined in 1947 to become the Department of Defense or DOD) and Commerce to join in founding a national standards organization.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] According to Adam Stanton, the first permanent secretary and head of staff in 1919, AESC started as an ambitious program and little else.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] Staff for the first year consisted of one executive, Clifford B.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] LePage, who was on loan from a founding member, ASME.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] An annual budget of $7,500 was provided by the founding bodies.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] In 1931, the organization (renamed ASA in 1928) became affiliated with the U.S.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] National Committee of the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), which had been formed in 1904 to develop electrical and electronics standards.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's members are government agencies, organizations, academic and international bodies, and individuals.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] In total, the Institute represents the interests of more than 270,000 companies and organizations and 30 million professionals worldwide.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's market-driven, decentralized approach has been criticized in comparison with more planned and organized international approaches to standardization.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] Although ANSI itself does not develop standards, the Institute oversees the development and use of standards by accrediting the procedures of standards developing organizations.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI accreditation signifies that the procedures used by standards developing organizations meet the institute's requirements for openness, balance, consensus, and due process.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI also designates specific standards as American National Standards, or ANS, when the Institute determines that the standards were developed in an environment that is equitable, accessible and responsive to the requirements of various stakeholders.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] Voluntary consensus standards quicken the market acceptance of products while making clear how to improve the safety of those products for the protection of consumers.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] There are approximately 9,500 American National Standards that carry the ANSI designation.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] The institute is the official U.S. representative to the two major international standards organizations, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), as a founding member, and the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), via the U.S.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI participates in almost the entire technical program of both the ISO and the IEC, and administers many key committees and subgroups.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] In many instances, U.S. standards are taken forward to ISO and IEC, through ANSI or the USNC, where they are adopted in whole or in part as international standards.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] Adoption of ISO and IEC standards as American standards increased from 0.2% in 1986 to 15.5% in May 2012.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] Each of the panels works to identify, coordinate, and harmonize voluntary standards relevant to these areas.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] In 2009, ANSI and the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) formed the Nuclear Energy Standards Coordination Collaborative (NESCC).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/american-national-standards-institute] NESCC is a joint initiative to identify and respond to the current need for standards in the nuclear industry.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/asc-x9] The **Accredited Standards Committee X9** (ASC X9, Inc.) is an ANSI (American National Standards Institute) accredited standards developing organization, responsible for developing voluntary open consensus standards for the financial services industry in the U.S.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/asc-x9] Membership in ASC X9 is open to all U.S. domiciled companies and organizations in the financial services industry.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/asc-x9] The committee was founded in 1974 under the American National Standards Institute, to develop financial industry standards following a surge in electronic banking, automated clearing, and data security needs.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/asc-x9] In 1984 it played a major role role in supporting the Check Clearing for the 21st Century Act (Check 21) through development of check image exchange and related standards.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/asc-x9] In the 1990s it expanded its cryptography standards, developing foundational specifications for secure data exchange and public key infrastructures (e.g., X9.42, X9.73, X9.24).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/asc-x9] In 2001, the organization was incorporated as ASC X9, Inc., transitioning from a pure ANSI committee to a non-profit industry consortium still accredited by ANSI.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/asc-x9] During the 2000s and 2010s it joined with international bodies like ISO/TC 68, helping shape ISO 20022 and other global standards for payments and securities messaging.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/asc-x9] The Accredited Standards Committee X9 develops, establishes, maintains, and promotes standards for the Financial Services Industry in the United States in order to facilitate delivery of financial services and products.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/austrian-standards-international] The first standard was published in 1921 on metric screw threads.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/austrian-standards-international] In 1932, the committee's name was shortened to the *Österreichischer Normenausschuss* (Austrian Standards Committee).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/austrian-standards-international] With the Austrian *Anschluss* to Nazi Germany in 1938, it became a branch office of the German *Deutsches Institut für Normung* (DIN) standards organization, but resumed operations in its own right after World War II, and was a founding ISO member in 1946.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/austrian-standards-international] The 1954 Federal Act on Standardization recognized the activities of the committee, and the Act, as amended, serves as its legal basis.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/austrian-standards-international] The Austrian Standards Committee's name was changed to *ON Österreichisches Normungsinstitut* in 1969.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/austrian-standards-international] On 1 March 2006, the Institute published ON rule ONR 168000, used to calculate the monetary value of a brand.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/austrian-standards-international] In 2018, the name was changed to Austrian Standards International.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/austrian-standards-international] The Institute is located at Heinestrasse 38, 1020 Vienna.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/austrian-standards-international] The acronym ÖNORM designates a national standard published by the Austrian Standards International and applicable to Austria alone.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/austrian-standards-international] Austrian national standards have the acronym "ÖNORM" followed by one letter and a unique number.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/austrian-standards-international] In the examples above, the letter "S" following "ÖNORM" indicates that these standards address topics not covered elsewhere (*Sonstige Normengebiete* in German).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] A **car**, or an **automobile**, is a motor vehicle with wheels.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Most definitions of cars state that they run primarily on roads, seat 1-8 people, have four wheels, and mainly transport people rather than cargo.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] There are over 1.6 billion cars in use worldwide as of 2025.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The French inventor Nicolas-Joseph Cugnot built the first steam-powered road vehicle in 1769, while the Swiss inventor François Isaac de Rivaz designed and constructed the first internal combustion-powered automobile in 1808.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The modern car—a practical, marketable automobile for everyday use—was invented in 1886, when the German inventor Carl Benz patented his Benz Patent-Motorwagen.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Commercial cars became widely available during the 20th century.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The 1901 Oldsmobile Curved Dash and the 1908 Ford Model T, both American cars, are widely considered the first mass-produced and mass-affordable cars, respectively.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Cars were rapidly adopted in the US, where they replaced horse-drawn carriages.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] In Europe and other parts of the world, demand for automobiles did not increase until after World War II.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] In the 21st century, car usage is still increasing rapidly, especially in China, India, and other newly industrialised countries.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Cars have controls for driving, parking, passenger comfort, and a variety of lamps.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Over the decades, additional features and controls have been added to vehicles, making them progressively more complex.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] These include rear-reversing cameras, air conditioning, navigation systems, and in-car entertainment.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Most cars in use in the early 2020s are propelled by an internal combustion engine, fueled by the combustion of fossil fuels.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Electric cars, which were invented early in the history of the car, became commercially available in the 2000s and widespread in the 2020s.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The transition from fossil-fuel-powered cars to electric cars is a central feature of most climate change mitigation scenarios.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] There are costs and benefits to car use.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The costs to the individual include acquiring the vehicle, interest payments (if the car is financed), repairs and maintenance, fuel, depreciation, driving time, parking fees, taxes, and insurance.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The costs to society include resources used to produce cars and fuel, maintaining roads, land-use, road congestion, air pollution, noise pollution, public health, and disposing of the vehicle at the end of its life.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Traffic collisions are the largest cause of injury-related deaths worldwide.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Personal benefits include on-demand transportation, mobility, independence, and convenience.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Societal benefits include economic benefits, such as job and wealth creation from the automotive industry, transportation provision, and societal wellbeing from leisure and travel opportunities.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] People's ability to move flexibly from place to place has far-reaching implications for society.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The English word *car* is believed to originate from Latin *carrus*/*carrum* "wheeled vehicle" or (via Old North French) Middle English **carre** "two-wheeled cart", both of which in turn derive from Gaulish **karros** "chariot".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] It originally referred to any wheeled horse-drawn vehicle, such as a cart, carriage, or wagon.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The word also occurs in other Celtic languages.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] "Motor car", attested from 1895, is the usual formal term in British English.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] "Autocar", a variant likewise attested from 1895 and literally meaning "self-propelled car", is now considered archaic.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] "Horseless carriage" is attested from 1895.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] "Automobile", a classical compound derived from Ancient Greek **autós** (αὐτός) "self" and Latin **mobilis** "movable", entered English from French and was first adopted by the Automobile Club of Great Britain in 1897.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] It fell out of favour in Britain and is now used chiefly in North America, where the abbreviated form "auto" commonly appears as an adjective in compound formations like "auto industry" and "auto mechanic".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] In 1649, Hans Hautsch of Nuremberg built a clockwork-driven carriage.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The first steam-powered vehicle was designed by Ferdinand Verbiest, a Flemish member of a Jesuit mission in China around 1672.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] It was a 65-centimetre-long (26 in) scale-model toy for the Kangxi Emperor that was unable to carry a driver or a passenger.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] It is not known with certainty if Verbiest's model was successfully built or run.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Nicolas-Joseph Cugnot is widely credited with building the first full-scale, self-propelled mechanical vehicle in about 1769; he created a steam-powered tricycle.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] He also constructed two steam tractors for the French Army, one of which is preserved in the French National Conservatory of Arts and Crafts.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] His inventions were limited by problems with water supply and maintaining steam pressure.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] In 1801, Richard Trevithick built and demonstrated his Puffing Devil road locomotive, believed by many to be the first demonstration of a steam-powered road vehicle.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] It was unable to maintain sufficient steam pressure for long periods and was of little practical use.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The development of external combustion (also known as steam) engines is detailed in the history of the car.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Still, it is often treated separately from the development of cars in their modern understanding.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] A variety of steam-powered road vehicles were used during the first part of the 19th century, including steam cars, steam buses, phaetons, and steam rollers.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] In the United Kingdom, sentiment against them led to the Locomotive Acts of 1865.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] In 1807, Nicéphore Niépce and his brother Claude created what was probably the world's first internal combustion engine (which they called a Pyréolophore), but installed it in a boat on the river Saone in France.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Coincidentally, in 1807, the Swiss inventor François Isaac de Rivaz designed his own "de Rivaz internal combustion engine", and used it to develop the world's first vehicle to be powered by such an engine.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The Niépces' Pyréolophore was fuelled by a mixture of Lycopodium powder (dried spores of the Lycopodium plant), finely crushed coal dust, and resin that were mixed with oil, whereas de Rivaz used a mixture of hydrogen and oxygen.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Neither design was successful, as was the case with others, such as Samuel Brown, Samuel Morey, and Etienne Lenoir, who each built vehicles (usually adapted carriages or carts) powered by internal combustion engines.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] In November 1881, French inventor Gustave Trouvé demonstrated a three-wheeled car powered by electricity at the International Exposition of Electricity.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Several other German engineers, including Gottlieb Daimler, Wilhelm Maybach, Siegfried Marcus, and Carl Benz were also working on cars and engines at about the same time.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] In 1879, Benz was granted a patent for a stationary engine.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] He had long dreamed of applying the internal combustion engine to produce a horseless carriage and began work on it in 1884.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] In 1885 he produced his first prototype car, the Benz Patent-Motorwagen Nr.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] On 29 January 1886 he applied for a patent for it, which was granted on 2 November of that year.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Benz further developed the Patent-Motorwagen, and had sufficient confidence in this to drive into Mannheim and have his vehicle written up in the *Neue Badische Landeszeitung* of 4 June 1886.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Benz' first production car, the Patent-Motorwagen Model 2, was produced in single-digit numbers in 1887–88.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Frenchman Émile Roger, already producing Benz engines under license, had added the Benz car to his product line in 1888.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Perhaps 60 of the Model 3 were produced between 1889 and 1893, the majority assembled in Paris from kits by Émile Roger.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Many historians consider Benz' advances so significant that they largely credit him as the inventor of the car and regard his 1886 patent as the birth of the modern car.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] In August 1888, Bertha Benz, the wife and business partner of Carl Benz, undertook the first road trip by an internal combustion engine car, to prove the road-worthiness of her husband's invention.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] In 1896, Carl Benz designed and patented the first internal-combustion flat engine, called *boxermotor*.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] During the last years of the 19th century, Benz was the largest car company in the world with 572 units produced in 1899 and, because of its size, Benz & Cie. became a joint-stock company.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The first motor car in central Europe and one of the first factory-made cars in the world was produced by the Czech company Nesselsdorfer Wagenbau (later renamed to Tatra) in 1897, the Präsident automobil.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Daimler and Maybach founded Daimler Motoren Gesellschaft (DMG) in Cannstatt in 1890, and sold their first car in 1892 under the brand name *Daimler*.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] It was a horse-drawn stagecoach built by another manufacturer, which they retrofitted with an engine of their design.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] By 1895, about 30 vehicles had been built by Daimler and Maybach, either at the Daimler works or at the Hotel Hermann, where they set up shop after disputes with their backers.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Benz, Maybach, and the Daimler team seem to have been unaware of each other's early work.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] They never worked together; by the time of the merger of the two companies, Daimler and Maybach were no longer part of DMG.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Daimler died in 1900, and later that year, Maybach designed an engine named *Daimler-Mercedes* that was installed in a specially ordered model built to specifications set by Emil Jellinek.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] This was a limited production run of vehicles for Jellinek to race and market in his country.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Two years later, in 1902, a new model of the DMG car was produced and named Mercedes after the Maybach engine, which generated 35 hp.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Maybach left DMG shortly thereafter and opened his own business.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Rights to the *Daimler* brand name were sold to other manufacturers.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] In 1890, Émile Levassor (who had bought a Benz Patent-Motorwagen Model 2 in 1888) and Armand Peugeot of France began producing vehicles with Daimler engines, and so laid the foundation of the automotive industry in France.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] In 1891, Auguste Doriot and his Peugeot colleague Louis Rigoulot completed the longest trip by a petrol-driven vehicle when their self-designed and built Daimler-powered Peugeot Type 3 completed 2,100 kilometres (1,300 mi) from Valentigney to Paris and Brest and back again.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] They were attached to the first Paris–Brest–Paris bicycle race, but finished six days after the winning cyclist, Charles Terront.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The first design for an American car with a petrol internal combustion engine was made in 1877 by George Selden of Rochester, New York.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Selden applied for a patent for a car in 1879, but the patent application expired because the vehicle was never built.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] After a delay of 16 years and a series of attachments to his application, on 5 November 1895, Selden was granted a US patent (U.S. patent 549,160) for a two-stroke car engine, which hindered, more than encouraged, development of cars in the United States.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] His patent was challenged by Henry Ford and others, and overturned in 1911.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] In 1893, the first running, petrol-driven American car was built and road-tested by the Duryea brothers of Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The first public run of the Duryea Motor Wagon took place on 21 September 1893, on Taylor Street in Metro Center Springfield.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Studebaker, subsidiary of a long-established wagon and coach manufacturer, started to build cars in 1897 and commenced sales of electric vehicles in 1902 and petrol vehicles in 1904.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] In Britain, there had been several attempts to build steam cars with varying degrees of success, with Thomas Rickett even attempting a production run in 1860.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Santler from Malvern is recognised by the Veteran Car Club of Great Britain as having made the first petrol-driven car in the country in 1894, followed by Frederick William Lanchester in 1895, but these were both one-offs.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The first production vehicles in Great Britain came from the Daimler Company, a company founded by Harry J.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Lawson in 1896, after purchasing the right to use the name of the engines.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Lawson's company made its first car in 1897, and they bore the name Daimler.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] In 1892, German engineer Rudolf Diesel was granted a patent for a "New Rational Combustion Engine".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] In 1897, he built the first diesel engine.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Steam-, electric-, and petrol-driven vehicles competed for a few decades, with petrol internal combustion engines achieving dominance in the 1910s.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Although various pistonless rotary engine designs have attempted to compete with the conventional piston and crankshaft design, only Mazda's version of the Wankel engine has had more than very limited success.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] All in all, it is estimated that over 100,000 patents have contributed to the modern automobile and motorcycle.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Large-scale, production-line manufacturing of affordable cars was started by Ransom Olds in 1901 at his Oldsmobile factory in Lansing, Michigan, and based upon stationary assembly line techniques pioneered by Marc Isambard Brunel at the Portsmouth Block Mills, England, in 1802.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The assembly line style of mass production and interchangeable parts had been pioneered in the US by Thomas Blanchard in 1821, at the Springfield Armory in Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] This concept was greatly expanded by Henry Ford, beginning in 1913 with the world's first *moving* assembly line for cars at the Highland Park Ford Plant.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] As a result, Ford's cars came off the line in 15-minute intervals, much faster than previous methods, increasing productivity eightfold while using less labour (from 12.5 manhours to 1 hour 33 minutes).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] It was so successful, paint became a bottleneck.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Only Japan black would dry fast enough, forcing the company to drop the variety of colours available before 1913, until fast-drying Duco lacquer was developed in 1926.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] This is the source of Ford's apocryphal remark, "any color as long as it's black".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] In 1914, an assembly line worker could buy a Model T with four months' pay.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Ford's complex safety procedures—especially assigning each worker to a specific location rather than allowing them to roam—dramatically reduced injury rates.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The combination of high wages and high efficiency is called "Fordism" and was copied by most major industries.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The efficiency gains from the assembly line also coincided with the US's economic rise.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The assembly line forced workers to move at a certain pace with very repetitive motions, which led to more output per worker, while other countries used less productive methods.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] In the automotive industry, its success was dominant and quickly spread worldwide, with the founding of Ford France and Ford Britain in 1911, Ford Denmark in 1923, and Ford Germany in 1925; in 1921, Citroën was the first native European manufacturer to adopt the production method.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Soon, companies had to have assembly lines or risk going bankrupt; by 1930, 250 companies that did not have assembly lines disappeared.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The development of automotive technology was rapid, due in part to the hundreds of small manufacturers competing to gain the world's attention.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Key developments included electric ignition and the electric self-starter (both by Charles Kettering, for the Cadillac Motor Company in 1910–1911), independent suspension, and four-wheel brakes.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Since the 1920s, nearly all cars have been mass-produced to meet market needs, so marketing plans have often heavily influenced car design.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Sloan who established the idea of different makes of cars produced by one company, called the General Motors Companion Make Program, so that buyers could "move up" as their fortunes improved.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Reflecting the rapid pace of change, makers shared parts with one another, resulting in lower costs across all price ranges.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Most British small-car assemblers, from Abbey to Xtra, had gone under.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Citroën did the same in France, coming to cars in 1919; between them and other cheap cars in reply such as Renault's 10CV and Peugeot's 5CV, they produced 550,000 cars in 1925, and Mors, Hurtu, and others could not compete.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Germany's first mass-manufactured car, the Opel 4PS *Laubfrosch* (Tree Frog), came off the line at Rüsselsheim in 1924, soon making Opel the top car builder in Germany, with 37.5 per cent of the market.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] In Japan, car production was very limited before World War II.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Only a handful of companies produced vehicles in limited numbers, and these were small, three-wheeled for commercial use, like Daihatsu, or the result of partnerships with European companies, like Isuzu building the Wolseley A-9 in 1922.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Mitsubishi was also partnered with Fiat and built the Mitsubishi Model A based on a Fiat vehicle.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Toyota, Nissan, Suzuki, Mazda, and Honda began as companies producing non-automotive products before the war, then switched to car production in the 1950s.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Kiichiro Toyoda's decision to take Toyoda Loom Works into automobile manufacturing would eventually lead to the formation of Toyota Motor Corporation, the world's largest automobile manufacturer.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Subaru, meanwhile, was formed from a conglomerate of six companies that banded together as Fuji Heavy Industries, as a result of having been broken up under *keiretsu* legislation.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Most cars in use in the mid 2020s run on petrol burnt in an internal combustion engine (ICE).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Some cities ban older, more polluting petrol-driven cars, and some countries plan to ban sales in the future.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] However, some environmental groups say this phase-out of fossil fuel vehicles must be brought forward to limit climate change.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Production of petrol-fuelled cars peaked in 2017.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Other hydrocarbon fossil fuels also burnt by deflagration (rather than detonation) in ICE cars include diesel, autogas, and CNG.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Removal of fossil fuel subsidies, concerns about oil dependence, tightening environmental laws and restrictions on greenhouse gas emissions are propelling work on alternative power systems for cars.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] This includes hybrid vehicles, plug-in electric vehicles, and hydrogen vehicles.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] As of 2025 one in four cars sold is electric but, despite rapid growth, less than one in twenty cars on the world's roads were fully electric and plug-in hybrid cars by the end of 2024.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Cars for racing or speed records have sometimes employed jet or rocket engines, but these are impractical for common use.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Oil consumption has increased rapidly in the 20th and 21st centuries because there are more cars; the 1980s oil glut even fuelled the sales of low-economy vehicles in OECD countries.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] In almost all hybrid (even mild hybrid) and pure electric cars, regenerative braking recovers and returns to a battery some energy which would otherwise be wasted by friction brakes getting hot.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Although all cars must have friction brakes (front disc brakes and either disc or drum rear brakes) for emergency stops, regenerative braking improves efficiency, particularly in city driving.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Cars are equipped with controls for driving, passenger comfort, and safety, normally operated by a combination of feet and hands, and occasionally by voice in 21st-century cars.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] These controls include a steering wheel, pedals for operating the brakes and controlling the car's speed (and, in a manual transmission car, a clutch pedal), a shift lever or stick for changing gears, and several buttons and dials for turning on lights, ventilation, and other functions.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Modern cars' controls are now standardised, such as the location of the accelerator and brake, but this was not always the case.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Controls are evolving in response to new technologies, for example, the electric car and the integration of mobile communications.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Some of the original controls are no longer required.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] For example, all cars once had controls for the choke valve, clutch, ignition timing, and a crank instead of an electric starter.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] However, new controls have also been added to vehicles, making them more complex.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] These include air conditioning, navigation systems, and in-car entertainment.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Another trend is the replacement of physical knobs and switches with secondary controls, such as touchscreen controls, such as BMW's *iDrive* and Ford's *MyFord Touch*.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Another change is that while early cars' pedals were physically linked to the brake mechanism and throttle, in the early 2020s, cars have increasingly replaced these physical linkages with electronic controls.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] More costly upper-class and luxury cars are equipped with features earlier such as massage seats and collision avoidance systems.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Dedicated automotive fuses and circuit breakers prevent damage from electrical overload.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Cars are typically fitted with multiple types of lights.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Interior ceiling lights in the car are usually fitted for the driver and passengers.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Some vehicles also have a boot light and, more rarely, an engine compartment light.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] During the late 20th and early 21st century, cars increased in weight due to batteries, modern steel safety cages, anti-lock brakes, airbags, and "more-powerful—if more efficient—engines" and, as of 2019, typically weigh between 1 and 3 tonnes (1.1 and 3.3 short tons; 0.98 and 2.95 long tons).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Heavier cars are safer for the driver from a crash perspective, but more dangerous for other vehicles and road users.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The weight of a car influences fuel consumption and performance, with more weight resulting in increased fuel consumption and decreased performance.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The Wuling Hongguang Mini EV, a typical city car, weighs about 700 kilograms (1,500 lb).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Heavier cars include SUVs and extended-length SUVs like the Suburban.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Some places tax heavier cars more: as well as improving pedestrian safety, this can encourage manufacturers to use materials such as recycled aluminium instead of steel.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] It has been suggested that one benefit of subsidising charging infrastructure is that cars can use lighter batteries.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Most cars are designed to carry multiple occupants, often with four or five seats.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Cars with five seats typically seat two passengers in the front and three in the rear.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Full-size cars and large sport utility vehicles can often carry six, seven, or more occupants, depending on seat arrangement.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] On the other hand, sports cars are most often designed with only two seats.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Utility vehicles like pickup trucks combine seating with extra cargo or utility functionality.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The differing needs for passenger capacity and their luggage or cargo space has resulted in the availability of a large variety of body styles to meet individual consumer requirements that include, among others, the sedan/saloon, hatchback, station wagon/estate, coupe, and minivan.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Mary Ward became one of the first documented car fatalities in 1869 in Parsonstown, Ireland, and Henry Bliss one of the US's first pedestrian car casualties in 1899 in New York City.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] There are now standard tests for safety in new cars, such as the Euro and US NCAP tests, and insurance-industry-backed tests by the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety (IIHS).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] However, not all such tests consider the safety of people outside the car, such as drivers of other cars, pedestrians and cyclists.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Some countries are tightening safety regulations for new cars, for example to mandate data recorders and automated braking.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The costs of car usage, which may include the cost of: acquiring the vehicle, repairs and auto maintenance, fuel, depreciation, driving time, parking fees, taxes, and insurance, are weighed against the cost of the alternatives, and the value of the benefits—perceived and real—of vehicle usage.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The benefits may include on-demand transportation, mobility, independence, and convenience, and emergency power.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Societal benefits may include economic benefits, such as job and wealth creation, from car production and maintenance, transportation provision, societal wellbeing derived from leisure and travel opportunities, and revenue generation from the tax opportunities.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The ability of humans to move flexibly from place to place has far-reaching implications for the nature of societies.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Trucks' share of US vehicles produced has tripled since 1975.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Though vehicle fuel efficiency has increased within each category, the overall trend toward less efficient types of vehicles has offset some of the benefits of greater fuel economy and reductions in pollution and carbon dioxide emissions.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Without the shift towards SUVs, energy use per unit distance could have fallen 30% more than it did from 2010 to 2022.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Car production and use have a large number of environmental impacts: it causes local air pollution plastic pollution and contributes to greenhouse gas emissions and climate change.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Cars and vans caused 10% of energy-related carbon dioxide emissions in 2022.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] As of 2023, electric cars produce about half the emissions over their lifetime as diesel and petrol cars.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] This is set to improve as countries produce more of their electricity from low-carbon sources.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Cars consume almost a quarter of world oil production as of 2019.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Cities planned around cars are often less dense, which leads to further emissions, as they are less walkable, for instance.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] A growing demand for large SUVs is driving up emissions from cars.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Cars are a major cause of air pollution, which stems from exhaust gas in diesel and petrol cars and from dust from brakes, tyres, and road wear.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Heavy metals and microplastics (from tyres) are also released into the environment, during production, use, and at the end of life.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Mining related to car manufacturing and oil spills both cause water pollution.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Animals and plants are often negatively affected by cars through habitat destruction and fragmentation caused by the road network, as well as pollution.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Animals are also killed every year on roads by cars, referred to as roadkill.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] More recent road developments are including significant environmental mitigation in their designs, such as green bridges (designed to allow wildlife crossings) and creating wildlife corridors.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Governments use fiscal policies, such as road tax, to discourage the purchase and use of more polluting cars; Vehicle emission standards ban the sale of new highly pollution cars.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Many countries plan to stop selling fossil cars altogether between 2025 and 2050.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Various cities have implemented low-emission zones, banning old fossil fuel and Amsterdam is planning to ban fossil fuel cars completely.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Some cities make it easier for people to choose other forms of transport, such as cycling.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Many Chinese cities limit licensing of fossil fuel cars.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Mass production of personal motor vehicles in the United States and other developed countries with extensive territories, such as Australia, Argentina, and France, vastly increased individual and group mobility and greatly expanded economic development in urban, suburban, exurban, and rural areas.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Growth in the popularity of cars and commuting has led to traffic congestion.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Moscow, Istanbul, Bogotá, Mexico City and São Paulo were the world's most congested cities in 2018 according to INRIX, a data analytics company.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] In the United States, the transport divide and car dependency resulting from domination of car-based transport systems presents barriers to employment in low-income neighbourhoods, with many low-income individuals and families forced to run cars they cannot afford in order to maintain their income.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Dependency on automobiles by African Americans may result in exposure to the hazards of driving while black and other types of racial discrimination related to buying, financing and insuring them.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Air pollution from cars increases the risk of a number of diseases, including stroke, heart disease, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), lung cancer, respiratory infections and aggravated asthma.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Air pollution is also linked to global impacts on all aspects of sexual reproduction from male and female fertility to fetal development, birth outcomes, and long-term health of offspring.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Children are extra vulnerable to air pollution, as their bodies are still developing and air pollution in children is linked to the development of asthma, childhood cancer, and neurocognitive issues such as autism.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The growth in popularity of the car allowed cities to sprawl, therefore encouraging more travel by car, resulting in inactivity and obesity, which in turn can lead to increased risk of a variety of diseases.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] When places are designed around cars, children have fewer opportunities to go places by themselves and lose opportunities to become more independent.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Intensive development of conventional battery electric vehicles is continuing into the 2020s, for example lithium iron phosphate batteries are safer and cheaper.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Other car technologies that are under development include wireless charging.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Software is increasing and may have many new uses, for example automatically not hitting pedestrians.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] New materials which may replace steel car bodies include aluminium, fibreglass, carbon fibre, biocomposites, and carbon nanotubes.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Telematics technology is allowing more and more people to share cars, on a pay-as-you-go basis, through car share and carpool schemes.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Communication is also evolving due to connected car systems.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Microwave weapons which can disable cars are being tested.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Fully self-driving vehicles, also known as autonomous cars, already exist as robotaxis in some locations.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Laws for the regulation of self-driving cars will need updating before widespread deployment can happen.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Car-share arrangements and carpooling are also increasingly popular, in the US and Europe.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Services like car sharing offer residents to "share" a vehicle rather than own a car in already congested neighbourhoods.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The automotive industry designs, develops, manufactures, markets, and sells the world's motor vehicles, more than three-quarters of which are cars.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] In 2020, there were 56 million cars manufactured worldwide, down from 67 million the previous year.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The automotive industry in China produces by far the most (20 million in 2020), followed by Japan (seven million), then Germany, South Korea, and India.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The largest market is China, followed by the US.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] There are around 1.644 billion cars in use worldwide as of January 2025; they burn over a trillion litres (0.26×10^12 US gal; 0.22×10^12 imp gal) of petrol and diesel fuel yearly, consuming about 50 exajoules (14,000 TWh) of energy.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The number of cars is increasing rapidly in China and India.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] In the opinion of some, urban transport systems based around the car have proved unsustainable, consuming excessive energy, affecting the health of populations, and delivering a declining level of service despite increasing investment.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Many of these negative effects fall disproportionately on those social groups who are also least likely to own and drive cars.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The sustainable transport movement focuses on solutions to these problems.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] The car industry is also facing increasing competition from the public transport sector, as some people re-evaluate their use of private vehicles.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] In July 2021, the European Commission introduced the "Fit for 55" legislation package, outlining crucial directives for the automotive sector's future.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] According to this package, by 2035, all newly sold cars in the European market must be Zero-emissions vehicles.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Established alternatives for some aspects of car use include public transport such as busses, trolleybusses, trains, subways, tramways, light rail, cycling, and walking.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Bicycle sharing systems have been established in China and many European cities, including Copenhagen and Amsterdam.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Similar programmes have been developed in large US cities.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Additional individual modes of transport, such as personal rapid transit could serve as an alternative to cars if they prove to be socially accepted.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] A study which checked the costs and the benefits of introducing Low Traffic Neighbourhood in London found the benefits overpass the costs approximately by 100 times in the first 20 years and the difference is growing over time.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] Motorsport is a sport involving high speed racing and drifting.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/automobile] It includes various racing series such as Formula One, IndyCar Series, NASCAR, World Rally Championship and MotoGP.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] A **backplane** or **backplane system** is a group of electrical connectors in parallel with each other, so that each pin of each connector is linked to the same relative pin of all the other connectors, forming a computer bus.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] It is used to connect several printed circuit boards together to make up a complete computer system.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] Backplanes commonly use a printed circuit board, but wire-wrapped backplanes have also been used in minicomputers and high-reliability applications.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] A backplane is generally differentiated from a motherboard by the lack of on-board processing and storage elements.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] A backplane uses plug-in cards for storage and processing.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] Early microcomputer systems like the Altair 8800 used a backplane for the processor and expansion cards.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] Backplanes are normally used in preference to cables because of their greater reliability.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] In a cabled system, the cables need to be flexed every time that a card is added or removed from the system; this flexing eventually causes mechanical failures.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] A backplane does not suffer from this problem, so its service life is limited only by the longevity of its connectors.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] For example, DIN 41612 connectors (used in the VMEbus system) have three durability grades built to withstand (respectively) 50, 400 and 500 insertions and removals, or "mating cycles".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] To transmit information, Serial Back-Plane technology uses a low-voltage differential signaling transmission method for sending information.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] In addition, there are bus expansion cables which will extend a computer bus to an external backplane, usually located in an enclosure, to provide more or different slots than the host computer provides.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] These cable sets have a transmitter board located in the computer, an expansion board in the remote backplane, and a cable between the two.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] Backplanes have grown in complexity from the simple Industry Standard Architecture (ISA) (used in the original IBM PC) or S-100 style where all the connectors were connected to a common bus.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] Due to limitations inherent in the Peripheral Component Interconnect (PCI) specification for driving slots, backplanes are now offered as **passive** and **active**.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] True passive backplanes offer no active bus driving circuitry.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] Any desired arbitration logic is placed on the daughter cards.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] Active backplanes include chips which buffer the various signals to the slots.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] The distinction between the two isn't always clear, but may become an important issue if a whole system is expected to not have a single point of failure (SPOF) .
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] Common myth around passive backplane, even if it *is* single, is not usually considered a SPOF.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] Active back-planes are even more complicated and thus have a non-zero risk of malfunction.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] Therefore, we are seeing newer architectures where systems use high speed redundant connectivity to interconnect system boards point to point with No Single Point of Failure anywhere in the system.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] When a backplane is used with a plug-in single-board computer (SBC) or system host board (SHB), the combination provides the same functionality as a motherboard, providing processing power, memory, I/O and slots for plug-in cards.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] While there are a few motherboards that offer more than eight slots, that is the traditional limit.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] In addition, as technology progresses, the availability and number of a particular slot type may be limited in terms of what is currently offered by motherboard manufacturers.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] However, backplane architecture is somewhat unrelated to the SBC technology plugged into it.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] There are some limitations to what can be constructed, in that the SBC chip set and processor have to provide the capability of supporting the slot types.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] In addition, virtually an unlimited number of slots can be provided with 20, including the SBC slot, as a practical though not an absolute limit.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] Thus, a PICMG backplane can provide any number and any mix of ISA, PCI, PCI-X, and PCI-e slots, limited only by the ability of the SBC to interface to and drive those slots.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] For example, an SBC with the latest i7 processor could interface with a backplane providing up to 19 ISA slots to drive legacy I/O cards.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] Some backplanes are constructed with slots for connecting to devices on both sides, and are referred to as midplanes.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] This ability to plug cards into either side of a midplane is often useful in larger systems made up primarily of modules attached to the midplane.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] Midplanes are often used in computers, mostly in blade servers, where server blades reside on one side and the peripheral (power, networking, and other I/O) and service modules reside on the other.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] Midplanes are also popular in networking and telecommunications equipment where one side of the chassis accepts system processing cards and the other side of the chassis accepts network interface cards.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] Orthogonal midplanes connect vertical cards on one side to horizontal boards on the other side.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] One common orthogonal midplane connects many vertical telephone line cards on one side, each one connected to copper telephone wires, to a horizontal communications card on the other side.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] A "virtual midplane" is an imaginary plane between vertical cards on one side that directly connect to horizontal boards on the other side; the card-slot aligners of the card cage and self-aligning connectors on the cards hold the cards in position.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] Some people use the term "midplane" to describe a board that sits between and connects a hard drive hot-swap backplane and redundant power supplies.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] Servers commonly have a backplane to attach hot swappable hard disk drives and solid state drives; backplane pins pass directly into hard drive sockets without cables.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] They may have single connector to connect one disk array controller or multiple connectors that can be connected to one or more controllers in arbitrary way.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] Backplanes are commonly found in disk enclosures, disk arrays, and servers.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] Backplanes for SAS and SATA HDDs most commonly use the SGPIO protocol as means of communication between the host adapter and the backplane.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] Alternatively SCSI Enclosure Services can be used.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] With Parallel SCSI subsystems, SAF-TE is used.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] A single-board computer meeting the PICMG 1.3 specification and compatible with a PICMG 1.3 backplane is referred to as a *system host board*.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/backplane] In the Intel single-board computer ecosystem, PICMG provides standards for the backplane interface: PICMG 1.0, 1.1 and 1.2 provide ISA and PCI support, with 1.2 adding PCIX support.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] The **British Standards Institution** (**BSI**) is the national standards body of the United Kingdom.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] BSI produces technical standards on a wide range of products and services and also supplies standards certification services for business and personnel.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] BSI was founded as the Engineering Standards Committee in London in 1901.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] It subsequently extended its standardization work and became the British Engineering Standards Association in 1918, adopting the name British Standards Institution in 1931 after receiving a Royal Charter in 1929.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] In 1998, a revision of the Charter enabled the organization to diversify and acquire other businesses, and the trading name was changed to BSI Group.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] The Group now operates in 195 countries.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] The core business remains standards and standards related services, although the majority of the Group's revenue comes from management systems assessment and certification work.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] In 2021, BSI appointed its first female chief executive officer, Susan Taylor Martin.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] BSI produces British Standards, and, as the UK's National Standards Body, is also responsible for the UK publication, in English, of international and European standards.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] BSI is obliged to adopt and publish all European Standards as identical British Standards (prefixed BS EN) and to withdraw pre-existing British Standards that are in conflict.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] However, it has the option to adopt and publish international standards (prefixed BS ISO or BS IEC).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] In response to commercial demands, BSI also produces commissioned standards products such as Publicly Available Specifications (PASs), Private Standards and Business Information Publications.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] These products are commissioned by individual organizations and trade associations to meet their needs for standardized specifications, guidelines, codes of practice etc.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] Because they are not subject to the same consultation and consensus requirements as formal standards, the lead time is shorter.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] BSI also publishes standards-related books, CD-ROMs, subscription and web-based products as well as providing training on standards-related issues.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] With 80,000 clients, BSI is one of the world's largest certification bodies.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] It audits and provides certification to companies worldwide who implement management systems standards.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] BSI also runs training courses that cover the implementation and auditing requirements of national and international management systems standards.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] BSI's best known product in the UK is the Kitemark, a registered certification mark first used in 1903.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] The Kitemark – which is recognized by 82% of UK adults – signifies products or services which have been assessed and tested as meeting the requirements of the related specification or standard within a Kitemark scheme.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] BSI also conducts testing of products for a range of certifications, including for CE marking.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] CE marking must be applied to a wide range of products intended for sale in the European Economic Area.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] Frequently, manufacturers or importers need a third-party certification of their product from an accredited or 'Notified' body.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] BSI holds Notified Body status for 15 EU Directives, including construction products, marine equipment, pressurized equipment and personal protective equipment.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] BSI also conducts testing for manufacturers developing new products and has facilities to test across a wide range of sectors, including construction, fire safety, electrical and electronic and engineering products.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] BSI provides regulatory and quality management reviews and product certification for medical device manufacturers in the Worldwide.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] It is the market leader in the US, the world's biggest healthcare market.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] In 2021, BSI Group, with support from the Construction Products Association, led the development of a product identification and traceability system known as *BSI Identify*.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] The initiative responded to recommendations made by Dame Judith Hackitt following her review of building safety, which called for wider adoption of permanent product marking and consistent labelling systems to improve traceability across the built environment sector.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] BSI Identify uses new Digital Object Identifier (DOI) technology "to deliver a unique, constant, and interoperable identifier", known as a BSI UPIN, "which can be assigned to products to help UK manufacturers to directly manage information about their products in the supply chain".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] The aim of the BSI Identify programme is that "wherever you are with [a] product, you can take a snapshot of the QR code with your mobile device, and it will immediately take you to the product technical data sheet.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/bsi-group] The BSI coat of arms was granted by the College of Arms in 1951.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/deutsches-institut-für-normung] In 1975, it was renamed again to **Deutsches Institut für Normung**, or 'DIN' and is recognised by the German government as the official national-standards body, representing German interests at the international and European levels.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/deutsches-institut-für-normung] The acronym, 'DIN' is often incorrectly expanded as **Deutsche Industrienorm** ("German Industry Standard").
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/deutsches-institut-für-normung] This is largely due to the historic origin of the DIN as "NADI".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/deutsches-institut-für-normung] The NADI indeed published their standards as **DI-Norm** (**Deutsche Industrienorm**).
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/deutsches-institut-für-normung] For example, the first published standard was '*DI-Norm 1*' (about tapered pins) in 1918.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/deutsches-institut-für-normung] Many people still mistakenly associate DIN with the old **DI-Norm** naming convention.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/deutsches-institut-für-normung] One of the earliest, and probably the best known, is DIN 476 — the standard that introduced the A-series paper sizes in 1922 — adopted in 1975 as International Standard ISO 216.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/deutsches-institut-für-normung] Common examples in modern technology include DIN and mini-DIN connectors for electronics, and the DIN rail.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/deutsches-institut-für-normung] DIN SPEC 3105, published in 2020, is "the first German standard to be published under an open license (CC-BY-SA 4.0) [...] to implement an open standardisation process".
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/deutsches-institut-für-normung] DIN is a nonprofit organization by German law.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/deutsches-institut-für-normung] The nonprofit owns *DIN Solutions GmbH*, which produces the DIN contents and *DIN Media* (formerly *Beuth Verlag*), which sells the DIN-standard manuals.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/deutsches-institut-für-normung] DIN is shareholder of *DIN Bauportal GmbH* and *DQS Holding GmbH*.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/deutsches-institut-für-normung] Some of the DIN standards date back to the time of Nazi Germany.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/deutsches-institut-für-normung] For example, standard DIN 5009, which describes the German Phonetic spelling code, is based on the postal spelling table, that was heavily edited by the Nazis.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/deutsches-institut-für-normung] Until 1934 it specified "D" for David, "S" for Samuel, "Z" for Zacharias and "N" for Nathan.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/deutsches-institut-für-normung] However, this went against the Nazis' ethnic-racial ideology and they decided to revise the letter board.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/deutsches-institut-für-normung] The postal spelling table was partially revised in 1950 and formed the basis for the first version of the standard in 1983.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/deutsches-institut-für-normung] The standard was revised again in 2022, using city names instead of person names.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/deutsches-institut-für-normung] DIN standards are not freely accessible to the public.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/deutsches-institut-für-normung] DIN sells subscriptions with the descriptions of the DIN-standards via DIN *Solutions GmbH* and *DIN Media*.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/deutsches-institut-für-normung] The majority of the standardization committees consist of representatives of the companies that are affected by the standards.
[src:deutsches-institut-für-normung/deutsches-institut-für-normung] DIN does not publish the names of committee members.
